The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Spectator critical 
                                                                                                                       7                                      Spectator critical 
            A STAFF REPORTER                      
	Calcutta: A spectator suffered serious injuries after a crude bomb exploded during the Mohun Bagan-East Bengal match at the Salt Lake Stadium on Friday.         
	Parimal Das (45), a resident of Khardah, suffered an abdominal injury when a crude bomb was hurled at the gallery after East Bengal took the lead through Robin Singh in the 12th minute. Dass friend, Biswajit Chakraborty, was also hurt in the explosion.         
	According to police, the incident occurred when the bomb exploded while East Bengal supporters broke in revelry at the C block of the stadium. Das was nearest to the explosion and suffered serious injuries. He was immediately taken out of the stadium and admitted to hospital, said an officer of the Bidhannagar south police station.         
	Das was immediately rushed to the AMRI Hospitals, Salt Lake, where he underwent surgery. Kalyan Kar, a general surgeon at the hospital, said: His intestine had come out and he also suffered a severe injury in the right arm. There was severe bleeding and his condition is extremely critical.         
	Doctors are trying to salvage his right arm and he has been put on ventilator, Kar added.         
	More trouble broke out after the match when spectators barged into the ground to congratulate East Bengal players. Four policemen were injured along with 10 spectators in the ensuing scuffle. Eleven people were arrested.                                                                                                                     
